title: Missing`upload_stream` documentation
body:
## Bug report for Cloudinary NPM SDK
The only reference to `upload_stream` in the documentation is [this example](https://cloudinary.com/documentation/upload_images#upload_data_stream). It doesn't show up in the [Upload API reference](https://cloudinary.com/documentation/image_upload_api_reference#signed_upload_syntax) which means there's no explanation of what the various parameters/options are, what's returned, caveats to its use, etc. I spent a great deal of time trying to figure out how to upload a string to a file, ultimately arriving at [an upload stream wrapped in a `Promise`](https://community.cloudinary.com/discussion/349/why-are-some-of-my-uploads-silently-failing-the-first-time-or-two) after reading [this GitHub issue](https://github.com/cloudinary/cloudinary_npm/issues/130). But it was far more confusing than it needed to be.

Note also that the example in the first link above uses the streamifier library when I think it's possible to just use a normal Node `Readable`. In my case, I was actually able to pass the string I wanted uploaded directly to `.end()`, so I didn't even need to create the stream myself.

It would be great to have some discussion of asynchronous considerations using streams in the documentation you write for `upload_stream`, even if all you do is mention that stream operations are always asynchronous and point to some MDN docs about how to properly use them. Bonus points for a Promise implementation, or some distillation of [this comment](https://github.com/cloudinary/cloudinary_npm/issues/130#issuecomment-417933120).

## Describe the bug in a sentence or two.
Missing documentation for `upload_stream`

title: Wrong response type from https://api.cloudinary.com/v1_1/<cloud>/auto/upload
body:
## Describe the bug in a sentence or two.
When uploading to `https://api.cloudinary.com/v1_1/<cloud>/auto/upload` API (the same as `cloudinarySdk.uploader.upload`), the returned type is `UploadApiResponse`. This works fine for uploads that upload the whole file at once but for partial uploads, the response is either a completely different object:

```
{
    done: false,
    bytes: 5242880,
    kind: 'upload',
    resource_type: 'image',
    public_id: '167d4ed2-c642-439e-b80b-c47ac97d085c/Y-JG-CANON-EOS-R7-0012'
```
